SCANSNAP

          A simple command-line tool that talks to Fujitsu ScanSnap
     iX500 scanners over WiFi. Put paper in, run the command, get a
     PDF. No daemon, no GUI, no dependencies beyond libc and pthreads.

          May also work with other ScanSnap models that use WiFi
     (iX1500, etc.) — reports welcome.


BUILD

          make

DOCKER

          Build:

              docker build -t scansnap .

          Show help:

              docker run --rm scansnap

          Scan to the current directory using a saved key:

              docker run --rm \
                -v "$PWD:/work" \
                -v "$HOME/.config:/config" \
                scansnap -s SCANNER_IP

          Notes:

          - The container includes the `ip` command because the tool
            uses `ip route get` internally to pick the correct
            interface.
          - Auto-discovery works best with host networking. On Linux,
            use `--network host`. On Docker Desktop, passing `-s IP`
            is usually the safer option.
          - `--getkey` needs the ScanSnap Home app to reach the fake
            scanner ports. That generally means `--network host`, or
            equivalent host-network support in your Docker runtime.

DOCKER COMPOSE WORKFLOW

          The compose setup is meant for a Linux host on the same LAN
     as the scanner. It persists two directories in the repository:

          - `./output` for scanned PDFs/JPEGs
          - `./config` for the saved pairing key

          Prepare the folders and build once:

              mkdir -p output config
              docker compose build

          One-time pairing key bootstrap:

          1. Turn off or disconnect the real scanner
          2. Start the fake scanner:

                 docker compose run --rm scansnap --getkey

          3. Open ScanSnap Home on your Mac or Windows machine
          4. Wait for the key to be printed and saved to:

                 ./config/scansnap/key

          Regular scans with the saved key:

              docker compose run --rm scansnap -s SCANNER_IP

          The PDF is written to `./output` because `/work` is bound to
     that folder inside the container. If you already know the pairing
     key, you can skip the bootstrap step and either put it in
     `./config/scansnap/key` or pass `-k KEY` manually.

          Important:

          - The compose file uses `network_mode: host` because the
            protocol setup needs the scanner to see the host IP and,
            for `--getkey`, to reach ports 52217, 53218 and 53219.
          - This is reliable on Linux. Docker Desktop on macOS/Windows
            can still build the image, but runtime communication with
            the physical scanner may fail because host networking is
            not equivalent there.
          - For custom output names, append normal CLI flags:

                docker compose run --rm scansnap -s SCANNER_IP -o /work/my_scan.pdf
          - If `--getkey` sees no traffic on a multi-homed host, run
            it in debug mode and force the advertised host IP:

                docker compose run --rm scansnap -d --getkey --getkey-ip HOST_LAN_IP


SETUP (one time)

          Your scanner is paired with a key — the serial number of
     its internal WiFi module. If the scanner was set up with the
     official ScanSnap Home app, that app knows the key, so we
     trick it into telling us:

     1. Turn off or disconnect the real scanner
     2. Run "scansnap --getkey" (needs ports 52217, 53218, 53219 —
        may need sudo)
     3. Open ScanSnap Home on your Mac or Windows machine — it will
        find the fake scanner and send the key
     The key is saved to ~/.config/scansnap/key automatically.
     You only need to do this once.


SCAN

          scansnap

          The scanner is found automatically on your local network.
     Pages come out as a timestamped PDF in the current directory.


OPTIONS

     -s IP       scanner IP (skip auto-discovery)
     -k KEY      pairing key from setup step
     -o FILE     output filename (default: scan_YYYYMMDD_HHMM.pdf)
     -j          save as separate JPEG files instead of PDF
     -1          single-sided (discard back pages)
     -d          debug output
     --getkey    capture pairing key (see setup)
     --getkey-ip IP
                 advertise this host IP in fake scanner mode


HOW IT WORKS

          The scanner speaks a proprietary protocol ("VENS") over
     UDP and TCP. See the PROTOCOL file for the full reverse-
     engineered specification.


